Module Documentation¶

oedtools.utils¶

oedtools.utils.generate_token_sequence(tokens, seq_length=10, sep=';', unique=True)[source]¶

Generates a string containing a sequence of tokens, randomly sampled from a given list or tuple of tokens, of a given length and separated by a given separator. Uniqueness of tokens in the sequence string holds by default, but can be turned off by setting unique to False.

Parameters

  • tokens (list, tuple) – The list or tuple of tokens to sample from

  • seq_length (int) – The length of the token sequence (and therefore the number of tokens in the string) - set to the minimum of the size of the token set and the requested length of the token sequence (default is 10)

  • sep (str) – The token separator - usually a single non-text character (default is ;)

  • unique (bool) – Whether the tokens in the sequence must be unique (default is True)

Returns

The token sequence as a sep-separated string

Return type

str

oedtools.utils.get_method(pkg_path)[source]¶

Returns a method given the full package path of the method, e.g. given the string oedtools.schema.get_schema it will return the actual method get_schema from the oedtools.schema module.

Parameters

pkg_path (str) – Full package path of the method

Returns

The actual method

Return type

function

oedtools.utils.get_value(val)[source]¶

Returns the number from a literal value if the value represents either an integer, real number or complex number. The use case is to extract numbers from string literals, if those literals are instances of one of three proper numeric types (int, float, complex). All other types of string are returned unchanged.

Parameters

val (None, bool, int, float, compex, str, bytes, tuple, list, dict, set) – The literal value, which can be any literal value

Returns

The number represented by the literal, if it represents a number, or the literal

Return type

None, bool, int, float, compex, str, bytes, tuple, list, dict, set

oedtools.utils.is_real_number(val)[source]¶

Simple method to check whether a literal value is a real number - returns True for integers as well.

Parameters

num (None, bool, int, float, complex, str, bytes, tuple, list, dict, set) – The literal value, which can be any literal value

Returns

Whether the value is a real number

Return type

bool

oedtools.utils.is_valid_token_sequence(tokens, seq, sep=';')[source]¶

Checks whether a string consists of a sequence of unique tokens from a fixed set of tokens, separated by a given separator. It is used to check the correctness of values in several OED columns such as (Acc|Cond|Loc|Pol|Reins)Peril and also (Acc|Cond|Loc|Pol|Reins)PerilsCovered, which must be ;-separated sequence of OED peril codes, e.g. AA1;WTC;WEC.

Parameters

  • tokens (list, tuple, set) – The iterable of tokens to check the string tokens against

  • seq (str) – The string to be checked

  • sep (str) – (Optional) The separator to use/expect - default is ;

Returns

Whether the string is valid

Return type

bool

oedtools.utils.sql_to_python_dtype(sql_dtype, as_numpy_dtype=False)[source]¶

Converts an SQL datatype string to a Python datatype string, or optionally a Numpy datatype string.

Parameters

  • sql_dtype (str) – SQL datatype string

  • as_numpy_dtype (bool) – (Optional) Numpy datatype string conversion option

Returns

A Python or Numpy datatype string

Return type

str

oedtools.utils.within_range(bounds_or_iter, val)[source]¶

Checks whether a given simple literal value (integer, float, string, bytes) lies within a given finite set of values or a bounded numeric range (or interval). If bounds_or_iter is not a range and

Parameters

  • bounds (tuple, list, set, range) – A finite set of values or bounded numeric range (or interval)

  • val (int, float, str, bytes) – The value to be checked

oedtools.values¶

oedtools.values.generate_values_profile(target_fp=None)[source]¶

Generates a JSON profile of values across key value groups described in the OED spec. such as construction codes/class, occupancy codes/types, peril codes, coverage types, deductible types and codes, limit types and codes, etc., as expressed in the input file columns.

This can be used to understand the structure of any value groups of interest, and also to validate actual values in the columns associated with any of these value groups, e.g. checking that the location level deductible code column for the buildings coverage type (LocDedCode1Building) only takes values in the set {1,2,3,4,5,6}.

Parameters

target_fp (str) – (Optional) The target file path to write the profile to

Returns

A values profile dict if no target file path

Return type

dict

oedtools.values.get_values_profile()[source]¶

Gets the values profile JSON (from oedtools/schema/) as a dict.

Returns

The values profile dict

Return type

dict

oedtools.values.get_column_range_by_value_group(header, values_profile=<values profile>)[source]¶

Gets the range of values of a given column from an OED input file (if present in the current master schema), using the information in the values profile.

Parameters

  • header (str) – Column header (case insensitive)

  • values_profile (dict) – (Optional) Values profile - this can save time for a caller applying this method on multiple columns

Returns

The column values range as a list if not null, or None

Return type

list, None

oedtools.values.get_column_validation_method(header, values_profile=<values profile>)[source]¶

Indicates how to validate the values in a given column, according to the values profile - the standard method is to use the column range as inferred from values profile, but any validation method in the package can be used, as long as it is specified as a lowercase string prefixed with func: and terminates with the full package path of the method.

Parameters

  • header (str) – The column header (case insensitive)

  • values_profile (dict) – (Optional) Values profile

Returns

The column validation method

Return type

str

oedtools.values.get_column_sampling_method(header, values_profile=<values profile>)[source]¶

Indicates how to sample the values in a given column, according to the values profile - the standard method is to use the column range as inferred from values profile, but any value-generation method in the package can be used, as long as it is specified as a lowercase string prefixed with func: and terminates with the full package path of the method.

Parameters

  • header (str) – The column header (case insensitive)

  • values_profile (dict) – (Optional) Values profile

Returns

The column sampling method

Return type

str

oedtools.schema¶

oedtools.schema.generate_schema(def_fp, target_fp)[source]¶

Generates a JSON schema from a CSV schema for a given OED file type (acc. loc., reins. info., or reins. scope), including the master file schema, and writes it to target file.

Parameters

  • def_fp (str) – Path of the CSV schema (data definition) file for a type of OED input file, e.g. loc., acc., reins. info. or reins. scope

  • target_fp (str) – The target file path to write the schema to

oedtools.schema.get_column_schema(schema_type, header)[source]¶

Gets the column schema (definition) for a given column in an OED acc., loc., reins. info. or reins. scope file, using a grouped version of the master file schema.

Parameters

  • schema_type (str) – OED schema type indicator (master, loc, acc, reinsinfo, or reinsscope)

  • header – The column header

Returns

The column schema

Return type

dict

oedtools.schema.get_grouped_master_schema()[source]¶

Gets the master schema grouped by schema type.

Returns

Master schema grouped by schema type

Return type

dict

oedtools.schema.get_schema(schema_type='master')[source]¶

Gets the schema of an OED input file - schema type must be one of acc, loc, reinsinfo, reinsscope.

Parameters

schema_type (str) – (Optional) File schema type indicator (master, loc, acc, reinsinfo, or reinsscope)

Returns

The schema dict

Return type

dict

oedtools.schema.get_schema_version()[source]¶

Gets the OED schema version - the schema version is stored in the schema_version.txt file in the schema subfolder. The version will correspond to the current Simplitium OED release version (1.0.3, as of 22/06/2019).

Returns

OED schema version

Return type

str

oedtools.schema.sample_column(schema_type, header, str_width=None, size=10)[source]¶

Sampling values in a given column in a given schema (acc, loc, reinsinfo, reinsscope), consistent with the validation method for the column (if there is one), or with the column range (if a column range is defined), or with the data type range.

Parameters

  • schema_type (str) – OED schema type indicator (master, loc, acc, reinsinfo, or reinsscope)

  • header – The column header

  • str_width (int) – Optional argument applicable only to string type columns with no defined column range and/or validation method. If applicable this option sets a fixed width for the individual string values sampled for the column

  • size (int) – Number of values to sample

Returns

Sampled values

Return type

list

oedtools.schema.update_schemas()[source]¶

A method to automatically re-generate the values profile JSON, and also all the file schemas, in oedtools/schema/.

oedtools.query¶

oedtools.query.get_columns(schema_types=None, headers=None, descriptions=None, required=None, nonnull=None, defaults=None, python_dtypes=None, sql_dtypes=None, numpy_dtypes=None)[source]¶

Queries the master schema for columns by header, and various properties including whether the column is required, non-null, and by default values, Python data types, SQL data types and Numpy data types. Multiple property types are combined into an “AND” query, e.g. specifying the required and nonull properties and header substring(s) will produce a list of column schemas for all columns whose headers contain the given header substrings and which are required by their respective file schemas.

Parameters

  • schema_types (list, tuple) – List or tuple of schema types - chosen from acc, loc, reinsinfo, reinsscope

  • headers (list, tuple) – List or tuple of column headers or (substrings of headers)

  • descriptions (list, tuple) – List or tuple of column descriptons or (substrings of descriptions)

  • required (bool) – Whether the column(s) are required (mandatory) in the relevant file(s)

  • nonnull – Whether the column(s) are non-null (must not contain null values) in the relevant file(s)

  • defaults (list, tuple) – List or tuple of default values

  • python_dtypes – List or tuple of Python data types (or substrings of data types) - chosen from int, float, str

type python_dtypes: list, tuple

Parameters

sql_dtypes – List or tuple of SQL dtype string (or substrings of data types) - chosen from bigint, bit, char, date, datetime, decimal, float, int, nchar, numeric, nvarchar(max), real, smallint, time, timestamp, tinyint, unsigned bigint, unsigned bit, unsigned int, unsigned smallint, unsigned tinyint, varchar, varchar(max), year

type sql_dtypes: list, tuple

Parameters

numpy_dtypes – List or tuple of Numpy data types (or substrings or data types) - chosen from float32, float64, int16, int32, int64, int8, object, uint16, uint32, uint64, uint8

type numpy_dtypes: list, tuple

Returns

(Possibly empty) sorted list of dicts, one per matching column. Sorting is by header

Return type

list

schema_version = '1.0.3'¶
validate(schema_type, file_or_data)[source]¶

Validates an OED input file, or an iterable of row dicts from an OED input file, against the corresponding OED schema for the given file type.

Parameters

  • schema_type (str) – The file schema type (loc, acc, reinsinfo or reinsscope).

  • file_or_data (str, list, tuple) – An OED input file path or row dict array

Returns

A dict array of results (one per column), the overall result (True or False), and the iterable of raw headers

Return type

list, str, list

validate_column(schema_type, header, data, column_pos=None)[source]¶

Validates column header and data. Results are yielded as a dict array, one per value

Parameters

  • schema_type (str) – The file schema type (loc, acc, reinsinfo or reinsscope).

  • header (str) – The column name

  • data (list, tuple, np.ndarray) – The column data iterable (list, tuple or Numpy 1D-array)

  • column_pos (int) – The index of the starting character of the column name in the column header line (if known or applicable)

validate_headers(schema_type, file_or_headers)[source]¶

Validates an iterable of OED input file headers (column headers), where the file type is specified using one of the following strings: loc for the loc. file, acc for the acc. file, The validation is a simple process of checking whether the given column headers correspond to columns defined in the current OED master schema and specifically the schema defined for the file type. Results are yielded as a dict array, one dict per header.

Parameters

  • schema_type (str) – The file schema type (loc, acc, reinsinfo or reinsscope).

  • file_or_headers (str, list, tuple) – An OED input file path or iterable of column headers from such a file

oedtools.report¶

oedtools.report.report_file(schema_type, file_or_data)[source]¶

Generates a validation report for the column headers and data in an OED input file or list or tuple of column headers.

Parameters

  • schema_type (str) – The file schema type (loc, acc, reinsinfo or reinsscope).

  • file_or_data (str, list, tuple) – An OED input file path or dict array of rows

oedtools.report.report_headers(schema_type, file_or_headers)[source]¶

Generates a validation report for the column headers in an OED input file or list or tuple of column headers.

Parameters

  • schema_type (str) – The file schema type (loc, acc, reinsinfo or reinsscope).

  • file_or_headers (str, list, tuple) – An OED input file path or dict array of column headers
